revision.text:
'''Abraham Baer ben Joseph Ezra Dobsewitch''' (or ''Dobsevage'') (born [[Pinsk]], Oct. 17, 1843; died [[New York City]], Jan. 14, 1900) was a Russian [[Hebraist]] and exegete.

== Life ==
At the age of thirteen Dobsewitch had written a commentary to the [[Canticles]]. In 1861 he went to [[Yekaterinoslav]], where he settled as teacher of Hebrew and contributed to various Hebrew periodicals. In 1874 he removed to [[Kiev]], where he became private tutor to the sons of Brodski and of other wealthy families. He went to the United States in 1891, and lived in [[New York City]], leaving it only for a short time in 1895.

Dobsewitch's chief published work is ''Ha-Meẓaref'' (''The Refiner''), a collection of rationalistic interpretations of various passages of the [[Aggadah]] (Odessa, 1870). Dobsewitch's two later works, ''Be-Ḥada Maḥeta'' (''With One Sweep''), a collection of articles (Cracow, 1888), and ''Lo Dubbim we-lo Ya'ar'' (''Neither Bears nor Forest'') (Berdyehev, 1890), as well as numerous articles in Hebrew periodicals, are devoted to criticisms directed against [[Moses Aaron Shatzkes|Shatzkes]], [[Isaac Jacob Weissberg|Weissberg]], and others. He continued his literary activity in the United States, and contributed to ''Ha-'Ibri'', ''Ner ha-Ma'arabi'', and various Yiddish publications. Some of his correspondence was published in ''Ha-Modi'a le-Ḥadashim'', i., New York, 1900.

Dobsewitch left several works in manuscript, including one on the [[Masoretic Text|Masorah]], one on the [[Samaritan Pentateuch|Samaritan text of the Pentateuch]], and one on the wit and humor of ancient Jewish literature. Short extracts from the last-named work were published in the United States.

