{{italic title}} {{dictdef}} '''''Les goddams''''' (sometimes '''''les goddems'''''<ref>Hughes, Geoffrey. (1998). ''Swearing: A Social History of Foul Language, Oaths and Profanity in English''. Penguin. p. 1. {{ISBN|978-0140267075}}</ref> or '''''les goddons'''''<ref>Calder, Nigel (1986). ''The English Channel''. Chatto & Windus. p. 185. {{ISBN|978-0701130534}}</ref>) is an obsolete [[ethnic slur]] historically used by the [[French people|French]] to refer to the [[English people|English]], based on their frequent [[Profanity|expletives]].<ref>Hitchings, Henry (2011). ''The Language Wars: A History of Proper English''. Hachette UK. p. 20. {{ISBN|978-0374183295}}</ref> The name originated during the [[Hundred Years War]] (1337–1453) between England and France, when English soldiers were notorious among the French for their frequent use of profanity and in particular the interjection "[[Wiktionary:God damn|God damn]]".<ref>Richards, Jeffrey. ''Films and British National Identity: From Dickens to Dad's Army''. Manchester University Press. p. 13-14. {{ISBN|978-0719047435}}</ref><ref>Hughes, Geoffrey (2006). ''An Encyclopedia of Swearing: The Social History of Oaths, Profanity, Foul Language, and Ethnic Slurs in the English-speaking World''. M.E. Sharpe. p. 324. {{ISBN|978-0765612311}}</ref><ref>Caunce, Stephen. (2004). ''Relocating Britishness''. Manchester University Press. p. 89. {{ISBN|978-0719070266}}</ref>
Outside France, the name has been used in [[French Canada|French-speaking parts of Canada]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.vehiculepress.com/tr_brierley.html |title = Long-dead Authors Make Amiable Companions: Translating Philippe-Joseph Aubert de Gaspé |accessdate = 2007-05-26 |authorlink = Jane Brierley |last = Brierley |first = Jane |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070630081812/http://www.vehiculepress.com/tr_brierley.html |archivedate = 2007-06-30 |df = }}</ref> Related terms have existed outside the French-speaking world: ''Godames'' was historically used in [[Brazil]], while ''Gotama'' was used in [[East Africa]].<ref> {{cite book |last= Burton |first= Richard F. |authorlink= Richard Francis Burton |title= [[The Book of One Thousand and One Nights|The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night]]: A Plain and Literal Translation of the Arabian Nights Entertainments |origyear= 1885 |url= |accessdate= 2007-05-26 |edition= volume 2, part 23 |year= 2006 |publisher= [[University of Adelaide|eBooks@Adelaide]] |location= [[Adelaide]] |chapter= Tale of Taj al-Muluk and the Princess Dunya (The Lover and the Loved) |chapterurl= http://etext.library.adelaide.edu.au/b/burton/richard/b97b/part23.html#fn1203}} Charles Johnston records the use of this word specifically for a soldier. (''Travels in Southern Abyssinia through the Country of Adal to the Kingdom of Shoa'' (London, 1844), vol. 1 p. 182 and note.)</ref>
