'''National School Choice Week''' was founded in 2011 to promote the concept of all forms of school choice: district schools, district [[magnet schools]], [[charter schools]], [[private schools]], and [[home schooling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gazette.com/national-school-choice-week-champions-better-education/article/1513571|title=National School Choice Week champions better education|author=|date=|work=Colorado Springs Gazette}}</ref> The week of events is scheduled the last week of January each year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.heartland.org/newspaper-article/2010/11/15/national-school-choice-week-kicks-january|title=National School Choice Week Kicks Off in January|author=|date=|publisher=}}</ref> As an organization it does not promote one form of educational choice over another,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://schoolchoiceweek.com/about|title=About|author=|date=|publisher=schoolchoiceweek.com}}</ref> but rather contends that parents should have and make choices in the best interest of their children.
==History== The week consists of independently organized events,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://redalertpolitics.com/2014/01/31/school-choice-week-is-almost-over-now-what/|title=School Choice Week is almost over — now what?|author=Shoshana Weissmann|date=|work=Red Alert Politics}}</ref> both large and small, in schools, state capitols, and other public meetings featuring the movement's signature yellow scarves. Additionally there are several national signature events and press opportunities. In 2011 there were approximately 150 events in over 30 states. Each year the participation has more than doubled. In 2014 nearly 6,000 events held in every state had a media contact with over 100 million households in the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/opinion/blogs/nina-rees/2014/01/28/national-school-choice-week-highlights-importance-of-empowering-parents|title=National School Choice Week Highlights the Importance of Empowering Parents - US News|author=Nina Rees|date=|work=US News & World Report}}</ref> In 2015, 11,082 events were held.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kicking Off School Choice Week With 9 Things You Need To Know|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maureensullivan/2015/01/26/kicking-off-school-choice-week-with-9-things-you-need-to-know/|accessdate=2015-09-21|first=Maureen|last=Sullivan}}</ref>
A number of notable and varied participants have spearheaded these events. Former [[WNBA]] basketball player [[Lisa Leslie]] teamed with Rep. [[Eric Cantor]] for a January 2014 event at Friendship Chamberlain Elementary School in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freebeacon.com/issues/students-rally-for-school-choice-in-d-c/|title=Students Rally for School Choice in D.C.|author=|date=|work=Washington Free Beacon}}</ref> [[KIPP]] co-founder [[Mike Feinberg]] gave an introductory speech at the 2014 National School Choice Week kick-off in Houston.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.houstonisd.org/news/2014/01/27/hisd-students-staff-join-national-school-choice-celebration-at-union-station/|title=HISD students, staff join national school choice celebration at Union Station|author=|date=|publisher=}}</ref> In 2013, the [[Jonas Brothers]] kicked off National School Choice Week with a concert in Phoenix.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://twitchy.com/2013/01/25/jonas-brothers-kick-off-school-choice-week/|title=Jonas Brothers kick off National School Choice Week|author=|date=|work=Twitchy}}</ref>
Highlighting the non-judgmental, non-partisan nature of the organization, the 2014 kick-off event paired conservative Republican Sen. [[Ted Cruz]] and Democratic stalwart Rep. [[Sheila Jackson Lee]] on the same stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourhoustonnews.com/ranch/news/cruz-jackson-lee-to-speak-at-national-school-choice-week/article_bcac7dee-360a-586c-8998-7c687d5dce28.html|title=Cruz, Jackson Lee to speak at National School Choice Week kickoff on Jan. 25|author=|date=|work=www.yourkatynews.com}}</ref> According to Cruz, "School choice is the civil rights issue of the 21st Century."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/01/30/the-issue-bringing-ted-cruz-and-black-democrats-together.html|title=The Issue Bringing Ted Cruz and Black Democrats Together|author=|date=|work=The Daily Beast}}</ref> In 2015, National School Choice Week opened with a nationally televised event in Jacksonville, Florida, featuring speeches NFL star [[Desmond Howard]], Democratic strategist Joe Trippi, and a video greeting by US Senator [[Marco Rubio]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redefinedonline.org/2015/01/thousands-celebrate-school-choice-jacksonville/|title=Redefined Online|date=|accessdate=|website=|publisher=|last=|first=}}</ref>
Governors and mayors across the country have issued resolutions and proclamations in support of the movement.<ref name="schoolchoiceweek1">{{cite web|url=http://schoolchoiceweek.com/press/403-21-governors-49-mayors-proclaim-school-choice-week-in-their-states-cities|title=21 Governors, 49 Mayors Proclaim ‘School Choice Week’ In Their States, Cities|author=|date=|publisher=}}</ref> The list of governors includes [[Bobby Jindal]], [[John Hickenlooper]], [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]], and [[Martin O'Malley]].<ref name="schoolchoiceweek1"/> Well-known mayors such as [[Marty Walsh (politician)|Marty Walsh]] and [[Kevin Johnson]] have also voiced their support.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20130131006382/en/29-Governors-Endorse-National-School-Choice-Week#.U8XFU41dXJE|title=29 Governors Endorse National School Choice Week As America’s Largest Education Reform Celebration Sweeps Across The Country - Business Wire|author=|date=31 January 2013|publisher=}}</ref> In 2015, the US Senate unanimously passed a bipartisan resolution recognizing School Choice Week across the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scott.senate.gov/press-release/senator-scott%E2%80%99s-school-choice-resolution-passes-us-senate|title=US Senator Tim Scott|date=|accessdate=|website=|publisher=|last=|first=}}</ref>
The President of National School Choice Week is Andrew Campanella.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://schoolchoiceweek.com/andrew-campanella|title=Andrew Campanella|author=|date=|publisher=}}</ref> On January 26, 2017, [[United States president]] [[Donald Trump]] made a [[Presidential proclamation]] stating that ''National School Choice Week, 2017'' started on that day.<ref>{{cite news|last1=[[White House Office of the Press Secretary|Office of the Press Secretary]]|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/01/26/president-trump-releases-national-school-choice-week-proclamation|title=National School Choice Week, 2017 Proclamation|work=[[whitehouse.gov]]|publisher=[[White House]]|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]|language=en|date=January 30, 2017|accessdate=February 11, 2017}}</ref>
